This article is a Presidential Proclamation from March 2012, declaring March as Women's History Month in the United States. The proclamation highlights the legacy of women pioneers who have fought for equality and justice throughout history. It mentions the role of Eleanor Roosevelt in addressing the status of women in America and the progress that has been made since then. The proclamation also discusses the efforts of the Obama Administration in promoting gender equality, such as workplace flexibility, increasing women's representation in math and science professions, and fighting for equal pay. It emphasizes the importance of women's perspectives and needs in foreign policy and peace-building efforts. The proclamation encourages Americans to celebrate Women's History Month and International Women's Day and invites them to learn more about the contributions of women throughout history.